article.description: Louisiana Tech has won 21 straight, and playing on the road simply does not rattle this team.
article.headline: Louisiana Tech keeps showing WAC who rules on road
article.linkText: Lady Techsters make their own road through Tulsa
article.story:
TULSA, Okla. (AP) -- Louisiana Tech has won 21 straight, and
playing on the road simply does not rattle this team.

	   "We've gone out and handled our business,'' coach Kurt Budke
said after his seventh-ranked Lady Techsters beat Tulsa 85-66
Saturday. "Everybody in this league is pretty good at home, but
everybody except ourselves is struggling on the road.''

	   Louisiana Tech (23-2, 15-0 Western Athletic Conference) is 12-1
away from home. The Lady Techsters became the first WAC school to
win at Tulsa (13-12, 8-6) this season.

	   Cheryl Ford finished with 26 points and 18 rebounds, her 13th
double-double in 15 conference games and 17th overall this year.

	   Ford had 19 points and 10 rebounds in the first half as the Lady
Techsters built a 47-31 halftime lead. She had nine points during a
20-1 run midway through the first half to give her team a 32-12
lead with 7:05 left in the half.

	   Ford also got Alyssa Shriver into foul trouble. Shriver, Tulsa's
second-leading scorer at 9.6 points a game, played only eight
minutes and was held scoreless before fouling out.

	   "The key for us every night is to get the ball inside. Alyssa
Shriver is a great player and causes teams problems,'' Budke said.
"We wanted to try and get her in foul trouble if we could. It
worked out. Cheryl had another huge game for us.''

	   Trina Frierson added 19 points and seven rebounds and Erica
Smith added 13 points and five steals for Louisiana Tech.

	   Allison Curtin, Tulsa's leading scorer, had 20 points but was
held to 5-of-16 shooting. Tulsa shot 36 percent and committed 22
turnovers.

	   Allison Carney had 15 points and TaTanisha Wagoner added 12 for
Tulsa.

	   After being held to eight points in the first half, Curtin
scored five points early in the second half to keep the Hurricane
close at 57-43 with 14:23 to play. But Louisiana Tech countered
with a 9-3 run to make it 66-46 with 11:51 left.

	   "We made one run,'' Tulsa coach Kathy McConnell-Miller said.
"It wasn't good enough or long enough and they answered.''
